         <abstract resp="pers:CD2">
            <p>
               <title level="a">Janet’s Family</title> is a one-act comedy of manners that satirizes the nouveau-riche of Calgary and illustrates Eaton’s longstanding interest in the permeability of class/caste. At the center of the plot are Janet Hawkins and her suitor, Alf Barker, a banker. Janet is lovely and irreproachable, but her family is not; the Hawkinses are a shallow, profligate bunch who each variously try to borrow money from Alf while he is calling on Janet. In May 1924, Eaton gave a reading of the play at a Little Theatre meeting, and three months later, the group was in rehearsal to stage a production at the Palace Theatre, directed by Eaton and Little Theatre club member Evelyn Hambly. Eaton’s daughter, Doris Babcock, was featured as Janet’s sister, Flossie. For scholars of the Canadian Little Theatre movement, this play provides rare insight into an original play written for the short-lived Calgary scene (1924-1932).</p>
         </abstract>
